service.name: Amazon CloudTrail
service.documentation: CloudTrail is a web service that records AWS API calls for your AWS account and delivers log files to an Amazon S3 bucket. The recorded information includes the identity of the user, the start time of the AWS API call, the source IP address, the request parameters, and the response elements returned by the service.

cabal.name: Amazon CloudTrail
cabal.description: CloudTrail is a web service that records AWS API calls for your AWS account and delivers log files to an Amazon S3 bucket. operations.name: CreateTrail
operations.documentation:
From the command line, use create-subscription.

Creates a trail that specifies the settings for delivery of log data to an Amazon S3 bucket.

operations.name: GetTrailStatus
operations.documentation: Returns a JSON-formatted list of information about the specified trail. Fields include information on delivery errors, Amazon SNS and Amazon S3 errors, and start and stop logging times for each trail.

operations.name: StopLogging
operations.documentation: Suspends the recording of AWS API calls and log file delivery for the specified trail. Under most circumstances, there is no need to use this action. You can update a trail without stopping it first. This action is the only way to stop recording.

operations.name: UpdateTrail
operations.documentation:
From the command line, use update-subscription.

Updates the settings that specify delivery of log files. Changes to a trail do not require stopping the CloudTrail service. Use this action to designate an existing bucket for log delivery. If the existing bucket has previously been a target for CloudTrail log files, an IAM policy exists for the bucket.
